@181  = ~Mage Robe~
@182  = ~Robes of Chaos~
@183  = ~Since the age of Netheril, mages have learned to bestow a wide variety of magical properties upon the everyday objects that surround them. A favorite item of such enchantment is the common robe. It is lightweight, affordable, and holds its enchantment well, thereby making it ideal equipment for a mage. Due to their magical heritage, however, only single-, dual-, and multi-class mages may wear these enchanted robes.~
@184  = ~Robes of Chaos:
  These robes are first believed to have appeared in the planes over a century ago. They came from the Plane of Pandemonium, and were first in possession of the mad wizard mayor of the town of Bedlam. However, it is not from this plane that robes gather their power. Sages believe that the robes are woven from the plane of Limbo itself, and that the plane, through these robes, is attempting to spread chaos through the multiverse. This theory is supported by the sheer immensity of power in these robes. Although records are hard to come by, it appears that the robes' abilities vary for each person wearing them, but that these powers will always maximize the person's ability to make chaos. The robes are themselves totally chaotic, varying in style, color, shape and transparency as you look at them. Wearing the robes is ill-advised to any mage, as they can simply vanish at any time, turn into a pit fiend, or catapult the wearer in a plane of eternal fire. The robes also surround the wearer with an aura of wild magic, meaning their spells sometimes become unreliable. Better known in planar magical circles as the Robes of "Oh my God, what's happening to me?!", these robes are certainly a magical curiosity and their immense power can make a wizard rival the Gods Themselves, or do distinctly unpleasant things to their spleen.  
  
  STATISTICS:
  Armour Class: 1
  Magic Resistance: 20%
  Save versus Death:  +3 bonus
  Immunity to Non-Magical Weapons.
  User affected with Wild Magic.
  Wearer receives a bonus to hit against all Lawful creatures.
  Some short of physical protection, though the nature of the robes makes this impossible to determine.
  Random Affects:
  Most of the robes effects are completely random and chaotic. The robes may grant powerful immunities, or burn the user into nothingness.
  Weight:  6~
@185  = ~Steal Spell Scroll~
@186  = ~This is the scroll given to you by the demon in the planar sphere. It needs to be cast near Wielter to steal the spell that will free the demon mages.~
@187  = ~Battle Axe~
@188  = ~Wizard Slayer +3~
@189  = ~The most common version of the battle axe is a stout pole about four feet in length with a single-edged, trumpet-shaped blade mounted on one end. This axe in particular appears to be very poorly made, and slightly smaller then the average battle axe.

  STATISTICS:
  Damage:  1D8
  Damage type:  slashing
  Weight: 7
  Speed Factor: 7
  Proficiency Type: Axe
  Type:  1-handed~
@190  = ~Wizard Slayer +3
  Though many weapons have used the name Wizard Slayer over the eons, this can truly be said to live up to it. Runes on the axe hum with magic, making it deeply ironic that the axe is a bane to all who wield sorceries. The axe's origin and history are unknown, but there is no doubt that mages should fear this weapon above all others.

  STATISTICS:
  When struck, there is a 20% chance that the mage will lose one spell from his memory.
  The axe has a bonus to hit against Mages.
  The axe also grants 25% Magic Resistance.
  Damage: 1D8 +3
  THAC0: +3
  Damage type:  slashing
  Weight: 6
